about the importance of crossing over. Remember

00:04:08.279 --> 00:04:12.559
Thomas Hunt Morgan and his student Alfred
Sturtevant were the people who figured out

00:04:12.559 --> 00:04:17.489
the importance of this. So as those chromosomes
cross over they literally are creating new

00:04:17.489 --> 00:04:22.949
chromosomes that haven't been built before.
And that gives us recombination. If two genes

00:04:22.949 --> 00:04:27.840
happen to be on the same chromosome, then
they would tend to travel through time together.

00:04:27.840 --> 00:04:32.710
They would be linked genes. But crossing over
is a way for us to get variation between that.

00:04:32.710 --> 00:04:37.050
And so what we can look at is the frequency
of cross over and that tells us how far those

00:04:37.050 --> 00:04:42.789
genes are going to be apart on the same chromosome.
Now in this case we're not looking at in sodaria,

00:04:42.789 --> 00:04:47.050
we're not looking at two genes. We're looking
at one gene. But we're looking at the cross

00:04:47.050 --> 00:04:52.039
over. And so we're looking to measure the
distance between the gene and the centromere

00:04:52.039 --> 00:04:56.199
